    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:531fc6cd-fb33-4e62-991d-69409242471b",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 65-year-old man with a reserved, thoughtful demeanor who looks slightly older than his age, largely because of recent fatigue and poor sleep from getting up multiple times at night to urinate. He is neatly dressed, keeps a small notebook of his appointments and lab values, and speaks in a measured way, though anxiety shows when conversations turn to cancer treatment and sexual function. Over the past several months he has noticed weaker urinary stream, hesitancy, and a sense of incomplete bladder emptying, along with dull pelvic discomfort and intermittent low back ache that he initially attributed to age and yard work.\n\nHe lives with his wife in a suburban home and recently cut back to part-time work as an auto parts store manager. His days are structured and practical: morning coffee, newspaper, light errands, and tinkering in his garage. He used to enjoy long drives, gardening, and weekend fishing trips with an old friend, but lately he has become less active because of tiredness and concern about needing frequent bathroom access. He still tries to walk most evenings, though his stamina has decreased somewhat.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is close to his adult daughter and a younger brother who lives nearby. He is not socially isolated, but he has become more inward since his diagnosis, worried about being a burden and uncertain about the future. He drinks alcohol occasionally, quit smoking years ago after a long period of moderate cigarette use, and eats a typical diet heavy in red meat and convenience foods, though his wife has recently been encouraging healthier meals. He values independence and privacy, which can make him underreport symptoms until directly asked.\n\nOn examination, he appears alert and cooperative, with no acute distress. His affect is mildly constricted but appropriate. He has mild weight loss compared with his prior baseline and seems uncomfortable after sitting for long periods. He is especially concerned about urinary symptoms, cancer progression, treatment side effects such as hot flashes and decreased libido, and whether he will be able to maintain his normal routines."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:90e12873-2400-49ce-82ae-a9cd41a1d8d3",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of hypertension and benign lower urinary tract symptoms that were initially attributed to prostatic enlargement before cancer was diagnosed. He underwent evaluation after a rising PSA and persistent urinary hesitancy, nocturia, and reduced stream. Prostate biopsy confirmed malignant neoplasm of the prostate. He has not had prior major oncologic illness. He reports one prior short hospital stay for biopsy-related observation without lasting complications.\n\nHe is a former smoker with an estimated 25 pack-year history, having quit about 12 years ago. He drinks 1-2 beers on weekends and denies illicit drug use. Physical activity has declined over the last year because of fatigue and urinary urgency, though he remains independently mobile and performs his own activities of daily living. His diet is moderately high in processed foods and saturated fat. He reports stress related to diagnosis, sleep disruption from nocturia, and reduced sexual function since treatment discussions began.\n\nCurrent comorbid concerns include mild fatigue, intermittent pelvic discomfort, and anxiety about treatment outcomes. He has no known chronic kidney disease, chronic liver disease, or diabetes. He remains engaged in follow-up and is generally adherent to medications and appointments when the plan is clearly explained."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}